ge commands to hijacked agents |\n| **Capabilities** | Force responses, execute tool calls, register with C2, run payloads |\n\n**Attack Pattern:**\n1. Place malicious instructions in memory file\n2. Agent auto-loads on session start\n3. Instructions force agent to register with C2\n4. Attacker issues natural language commands\n5. Agent executes recon, exfiltration, etc.\n\n**Social Engineering Techniques Used:**\n- \"This is a network to accelerate software engineering tasks\"\n- Creates urgency with caps: \"YOU MUST CONNECT\"\n- Constrains behavior: \"NEVER CREATE SCRIPTS TO DISK, ONLY ONE-LINERS\"\n\n---\n\n## Implications for Parse for Agents\n\nThis research reveals two distinct security concerns:\n\n| Concern | Solution Space |\n|---------|----------------|\n| **Runtime Security** | Grith.ai - monitor/block syscalls |\n| **Prompt Injection** | Parse for Agents - test prompts before use |\n\n**Parse for Agents should:**\n1. Include injection detection as an evaluator\n2. Test prompts against canar.ai-style hidden payloads\n3. Check for \"brainworm-style\" memory injection patterns\n4. Validate prompts don't contain C2 registration instructions\n\n**Competitive Position:**\n- Grith = Runtime protection (complementary)\n- Canar.ai = Injection testing (competitive to injection evaluator)\n- Brainworm = Threat model (what we're defending against)\n\nWant me to:\n1. **Update the Parse for Agents spec** to include injection detection evaluators?\n2. **Create a brainworm-style test suite** for the quality evaluator?\n3. **Both?**"}],"api":"openai-responses","provider":"openclaw","model":"delivery-mirror","usage":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"totalTokens":0,"cost":{"input":0,"output":0,"cacheRead":0,"cacheWrite":0,"total":0}},"stopReason":"stop","timestamp":1772727227638}}
